<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Thomson, John. Journal, Mackenzie River, 1800-1802. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0021</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">Sunday the 5<sup>th</sup><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Very Cold Weather<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Long before daylight departed<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Carried the sail a little.  Encamped at Sunset on Island at the other side of the last Traverse &#8211; a great deal of Snow on the ground &amp; some Ice along the shore, in short the Country bears as dreary an aspect as on the midst of Winter<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  N.B. Smith this morning embarked his Wife and two Children but not until after he had made use of many arguments &amp; much coaxing to make her consent<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Monday the 6<sup>th</sup><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Wind Bound.  Snowed very hard all day<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Tuesday the 7<sup>th</sup><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Set off after sun rise, carried a light sail all day.  Encamped at the River au Foin &#8211; it was not without apparently iniminent danger that we gained the Entrance of the River owing to a very heavy swell<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Wednesday the 8<sup>th</sup><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The weather continually very Cold<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[E]</span>ncamped (thank God) at the End of the Slave Lake &#8211; after a very quick passage of only 4 days<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Thursday the 9<sup>th</sup><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Set off in the night<span class="AddHand-editors">[,]</span> carried sail most part of the day.  Encamped below the second Little Lake<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Severe cold<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Friday the 10<sup>th</sup><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Decamped about midnight &amp; in the morning arrived at the Fort &#8211; found La Prise all alone there with his Two wives &#8211; he has made a little Provissions indeed much more than I expected would have been made &#8211; he has not done any work all Summer on account of as he says Bad health<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The few Indians that passed the summer here are hunting near hand<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Received the Loadings.  Took an Inventory of the Property found here &amp; an acc<sup>t</sup> of the Goods that Remain &#8211; &amp; Gave out the remainder to 2 canoes for the Rocky Mountain, say 21 Pieces of Goods &amp; 4 do of Provissions<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Gave the Men a Dram<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Saturday the 11<sup>th</sup><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Early this morning took my departure for the Rocky Mountain, with 2 canoes</p>
<p style="text-align:right;">Manned</p>

<p align="page-number"><span class="AddHand-editors">[3]</span></p>

